be forcefully expired after normal expiration","Volume of air that cannot be expired from the lungs"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETidal volume is defined as the \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air moved in or out during normal quiet breathing\u003C/strong\u003E. In an average adult man, this is typically around 500 mL, and in an average adult woman, it is around 400 mL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air remaining in lungs after maximal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E and the \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air that cannot be expired from the lungs\u003C/strong\u003E both describe the residual volume. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air that can be forcefully inspired after normal inspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is the inspiratory reserve volume, which is the additional air that can be inhaled beyond a normal breath. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evolume of air that can be forcefully expired after normal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E is the expiratory reserve volume, which is the additional air that can be exhaled beyond a normal breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding lung volumes is essential for assessing respiratory function. Tidal volume forms the basis for calculating minute ventilation (tidal volume \u00d7 respiratory rate) and is an important parameter in mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tidal volume is the volume of air moved in or out of the lungs during normal quiet breathing.","Dead space volume is approximately 150 mL in adults and represents air that does not participate in gas exchange."],"references":["West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 2;  pg. 16.","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10533"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116757"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{